in the intrinsic muscles of the hand, with a noticeable \u0027claw hand\u0027 deformity. Sensation is reduced over the medial aspect of the forearm and hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is expected in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Impairment in C8 and T1 myotomes","Weak biceps reflex","Impairment in C5 and C6 myotomes","Weak triceps reflex","Impairment in C7 myotome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpairment in C8 and T1 myotomes\u003C/strong\u003E is expected in Klumpke\u0027s palsy, as this condition results from injury to the lower brachial plexus, specifically affecting these nerve roots. This leads to weakness in the intrinsic muscles of the hand and a \u0027claw hand\u0027 deformity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeak biceps reflex\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with Klumpke\u0027s palsy, as the biceps reflex is mediated by the C5 and C6 nerve roots, which are not typically affected in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpairment in C5 and C6 myotomes\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of an upper brachial plexus injury, not Klumpke\u0027s palsy. Such an injury would affect shoulder abduction and elbow flexion, not the intrinsic hand muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeak triceps reflex\u003C/strong\u003E is not expected in Klumpke\u0027s palsy, as the triceps reflex is mediated by the C7 nerve root, which is not involved in this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpairment in C7 myotome\u003C/strong\u003E would affect the triceps and wrist extensors, which are not typically involved in Klumpke\u0027s palsy. This condition primarily affects the muscles innervated by the C8 and T1 nerve roots.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Klumpke\u0027s palsy results from injury to the lower brachial plexus, specifically affecting the C8 and T1 nerve roots.","This condition typically leads to weakness in the muscles innervated by these nerve roots, including intrinsic hand muscles.","A characteristic sign of Klumpke\u0027s palsy is the \u0027claw hand\u0027 deformity due to paralysis of the intrinsic muscles of the hand."],"references":["Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Science","Merryman J, Varacallo M. Klumpke Palsy. 2023 Aug 4. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30285395."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17304"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64081"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:59:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T16:01:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9994"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78737"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Sui